# Java Conventions

## Naming
- **Controllers**: `*Controller` | **Services**: `*Service` | **Repositories**: `*Repository`
- **Entities**: `*Entity` | **DALs**: `*Dal` | **Mappers**: `*Mapper` (MapStruct)
- **Exceptions**: `*Exception` with `@Getter` for context fields

## Lombok
- `@Log4j2` for logging — **never** `@Slf4j`
- `@Getter`/`@Setter`, `@Builder`, `@NoArgsConstructor`/`@AllArgsConstructor`
- Entity-specific annotations (`@Accessors`, `@EqualsAndHashCode`) → see `persistence-patterns.mdc`

## Dependency Injection
- **Constructor injection only** — no `@Autowired` on fields
- `@Autowired(required = false)` only for genuinely optional beans
- `@Value("${property:default}")` for config properties

## Logging
```java
log.info("Processing request id=[{}] status=[{}]", id, status);
log.atDebug().log(() -> "Expensive: " + expensiveCall());
```
- Parameterized messages — never concatenate strings
- Always include contextual IDs in log messages
- Exception as **last** argument: `log.error("Failed id=[{}]", id, e);`

## Error Handling

### Custom Exceptions
```java
@Getter
public class ResourceNotFoundException extends RuntimeException {
    private final String resourceId;
    public ResourceNotFoundException(String resourceId) {
        super("Resource not found: " + resourceId);
        this.resourceId = resourceId;
    }
}
```
- Extend `RuntimeException` (unchecked), use `@Getter` for context fields

### Controller Error Mapping
- Throw `ResponseStatusException` for HTTP status mapping
- Centralized handler converts to RFC 7807 Problem Details
- All API errors return `type`, `title`, `status`, `detail`, `instance` fields

## Import Ordering
- No wildcard imports — always explicit
- Group: `java.*` → `javax.*`/`jakarta.*` → company packages → third-party

## Null Handling
- `@NotNull` for method parameters that must not be null
- `Optional<T>` for return types that may be absent — never for parameters or fields
- `Objects.requireNonNull(param, "message")` in constructors

## Collections & Immutability
- Prefer `List.of()`, `Set.of()`, `Map.of()` for immutable collections
- `new ArrayList<>()` only when mutation is required

## Java 17 Features
- **Records** for pure data carriers: `record Foo(String bar, int baz) {}`
- **Text blocks** for multi-line strings (SQL, JSON templates)
- **Pattern matching**: `if (obj instanceof String s) { ... }`
- `"text %s".formatted(val)` over `String.format()`
